Condition : 4 - Prior to the commencement of development at the site a detailed Construction Logistics Plan (CLP) shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. Development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved CLP which shall remain in force for the entire construction period.
The CLP shall be informed by the Construction Logistic Planning Guidance prepared by Construction Logistics in association with Transport for London. It must cover as a minimum:
 a plan showing the area to be surveyed to establish existing public highway condition;
 a pre-start record of the conditions of the public highway identified by the plan referred to above, undertaken in consultation with Hounslow Highways/TfL and a written commitment to repair any damage caused by the carrying out of the development, in accordance with a timetable to have been previously agreed in writing by the local planning authority;
 on-site parking and turning provision for site operatives, visitors and construction vehicles;
 provision for the loading, unloading and storage of plant and materials within the site;  location of temporary offices, contractors compounds and welfare facilities within the site;
details of points of access and egress to and from the site for construction traffic;
 details of signage at all vehicular exits from the construction site advising drivers of preferred routes;
 the erection and maintenance of security hoardings, including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing where appropriate;
 all works of demolition and construction to take place only between the hours of 08.00 and 18.00 Monday to Friday and 09.00 and 13.00 on Saturdays and at no time on Sundays or Bank/Public Holidays;
 all site deliveries to take place between the hours of 09.30 and 15.00 Monday to Saturdays and at no time on Sundays or Bank/Public Holidays;
 details of measures to prevent the deposition of mud and debris on the public highway, including wheel wa

Condition : 5 - Prior to the commencement of the development, including any demolition works and site preparation, a detailed Construction Environment Management Plan (CEMP) shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The CEMP shall provide details of how demolition and construction works are to be undertaken and include:
i. The identification of stages of works;
ii. measures to mitigate noise, dust and air quality;
iii. details of working hours, which unless otherwise agreed with the Local Planning Authority shall be limited to 08:00 to 18:00 Monday to Friday and 08:00 to 13:00 on Saturdays);
iv. Procedures for maintaining good public relations including complaint management, public consultation and liaison;
v. Mitigation measured as defined in BS 5228: Parts 1 and 2: 2009 Noise and Vibration Control on Construction and Open Sites shall be used to minimise noise disturbance from construction works;
vi. Measures to control emissions during the construction phase in line with the requirements of the Mayor?s Control of Dust and Emissions during Construction and Demolition SPG.
The approved CEMP shall be adhered to throughout the construction period of each phase of the development

Condition : 12 - Prior to the commencement of development above slab level, details of both hard and soft landscape works shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. Development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details. The details to be submitted shall include:
soft planting: including any grass and turf areas, trees, planters, shrub and herbaceous areas including details of species, sizes, numbers/densities and sections of landscaped areas;
?h a 'Tree Planting Statement' providing full details, locations, specifications and construction methods for all purpose-built tree pits and associated above ground features, including specifications for tree protection and a stated volume of suitable growing medium to facilitate and promote the healthy development of the proposed trees;
?h hard landscaping: including ground surfaces, kerbs, edges, ridge and flexible paving, furniture, steps, refuse disposal points and, where relevant, synthetic surfaces for both  ground level and roof terrace level;
 fences and walls and any other boundary treatments;
 quiet zones;
 outdoor play spaces and play equipment
 any signage and information boards;
 brown and green (biodiversity) roofs and green walls;
 any CCTV equipment;
 an external lighting strategy;
 any other landscaping features forming part of the scheme;
 a timetable for implementation and completion of the landscaping scheme;
 details of wind mitigation measures and,
 a comprehensive Landscape Management and Maintenance Plan for the lifetime of the development, which shall include long term design objectives, management responsibilities and maintenance schedules for all hard and soft landscape areas, and details of safety measures for landscaping positioned at height.

Condition : 19 - A. Prior to the commencement of above slab level, details of a scheme to secure the following shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority:
? at least three of the key elements of the building envelope (external walls, windows, roof, upper floor slabs, internal walls, floor finishes/coverings) are to achieve a rating of A+ to D in the Building Research Establishment (BRE) The Green Guide of specification;
? at least 50% of timber and timber products used are to be sourced from accredited Forest Stewardship Council (FSC) or Programme for the Endorsement of Forestry Certification (PEFC) schemes as set out in the Mayor of London's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG;
? details of the measures taken to avoid construction or insulation materials which would release toxins into the internal and external environment, including those that deplete stratospheric ozone.
B. The development hereby approved shall not be occupied until evidence (e.g. photographs and copies of installation contracts) has been submitted to and agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority to demonstrate that the development has been carried out in accordance with the approved details under Part A of this condition. The development shall be maintained in accordance with the approved details at all times thereafter.C. Prior to first occupation of any part of the development hereby approved, a detailed Whole Life Cycle Carbon assessment shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, demonstrating that the Whole Life Cycle Carbon emissions savings of the development achieve the GLA benchmarks set out in the GLA's Whole Life-Cycle Assessment Guidance. The assessment shall include details of measures to reduce carbon emissions throughout the whole life cycle of the development and provide calculations in line with the Mayor of London's guidance on Whole Life Cycle Carbon Assessments

Condition : 39 - Maximum noise levels within the dwellings hereby approved shall not exceed:
Living Rooms = 35 dB LAeq, 16hour;
Dining room/area = 40 dB LAeq, 16hour;
Bedroom = 35 dB LAeq, 16 hours during daytime (07:00 - 23:00) and 30 dB LAeq, 8hour in the night time (23:00 - 07:00). LAmax noise levels within bedrooms shall not typically exceed 45 dB LAmax more than 15 times per night.
The maximum noise levels described must be achieved during background ventilation rates as defined in Part F of the Building Regulations.

Condition : 42 - Notwithstanding any details included in the submitted plans, no dwelling hereby approved shall be occupied until details of private amenity space for each dwelling have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. These details shall include:
(a)	a statement setting out the design objectives and demonstrating high quality amenity space provision for all dwellings; 
(b)	area of private amenity space for each dwelling;
(c)	details of provision of winter gardens; 
The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details before the residential element of the development hereby permitted is first occupied or brought into use and so maintained at all times thereafter.
